---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import SidebarLayout from '../../components/shared/SidebarLayout.astro';

import { surgeryNavItems as navItems } from '../../data/surgeryNavItems';
---

<Layout description="Surgical procedures for orthodontics including impacted tooth exposure, tooth extractions, and skeletal anchorage. Working with your orthodontist for optimal results."
  title="Orthodontic Surgery Windsor | Great Lakes Oral Surgery">
  <script type="application/ld+json" slot="head">{JSON.stringify({ "@context": "https://schema.org", "@graph": [
    { "@type": "MedicalWebPage", "name": "Surgery for Orthodontics", "url": "https://www.greatlakessurgerycentre.com/surgery/orthodontic-surgery", "description": "Surgical procedures for orthodontics including impacted tooth exposure, tooth extractions, autotransplantation, and skeletal anchorage in Windsor, Ontario.", "specialty": "Oral and Maxillofacial Surgery" },
    { "@type": "MedicalProcedure", "name": "Orthodontic Surgery", "procedureType": "Surgical", "bodyLocation": "Jaw, teeth", "description": "Surgical procedures performed in collaboration with orthodontists, including removal of retained primary teeth, exposure of impacted teeth, autotransplantation, skeletal anchorage screw placement, and frenectomies.", "indication": "Impacted permanent teeth that fail to erupt, crowding requiring premolar extraction, impacted tooth requiring bracket placement, diastema from frenum attachment." },
    { "@type": "FAQPage", "mainEntity": [
      { "@type": "Question", "name": "What is surgical exposure of an impacted tooth?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "When a permanent tooth fails to erupt at the expected time, the orthodontist requests surgical exposure. The surgeon removes the bone and gum tissue covering the impacted tooth and places an orthodontic bracket on it. The orthodontist then applies force to move the tooth into its proper position." } },
      { "@type": "Question", "name": "What is autotransplantation?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Autotransplantation involves removing an unerupted tooth from a less important area and surgically placing it into a more important area where a tooth is missing, allowing it to develop in its new position." } },
      { "@type": "Question", "name": "What is skeletal anchorage in orthodontics?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Skeletal anchorage involves surgically inserting small titanium screws into the upper or lower jawbones. These screws protrude through the gum tissue and the orthodontist uses them as anchors to apply force to move teeth. Once the desired movement is achieved, the screws are removed." } }
    ]}
  ]})}</script>
  <SidebarLayout title="Our Procedures" navItems={navItems} currentPath={Astro.url.pathname} eyebrow="Surgical Procedures" heroSubtitle="Expert oral and maxillofacial surgical procedures performed with precision and care.">
    <Fragment slot="card-header">
      <h2>Surgery for Orthodontics</h2>
      <p>Many patients are referred by area orthodontists for surgical procedures — from removing retained teeth and creating space, to exposing impacted teeth for proper alignment.</p>
    </Fragment>

    <div class="leading-relaxed space-y-4" style="color: #515151">
      <p>Many patients are referred to our practice by area orthodontists. Their orthodontists will request we perform a surgical procedure that will then permit the orthodontists to properly align the patients teeth. Sometimes, this is as simple as removing some retained primary ("baby") teeth, removing some permanent premolars to create space if there is too much crowding, or removing wisdom teeth after the other teeth are orthodontically aligned so that the developing wisdom teeth don't adversely affect the teeth in front of them.</p>
      <p>In more involved cases, some permanent teeth may fail to erupt at the expected time. If this occurs, the orthodontist will request surgical exposure of an impacted tooth. This consists of removing the bone and gum tissue covering a tooth embedded in the bone so that an orthodontic bracket may be placed. This will provide the orthodontist access to that embedded tooth so that they can apply a force to it and bring it to its proper position.</p>
      <p>In some situations there is a missing tooth in a very important area of the mouth. Certain cases may dictate removing an unerupted tooth in a less important area and placing it surgically into this very important area for it to develop. This is called autotransplantation. In other instances, certain situations will dictate the use of skeletal anchorage. This consists of surgically inserting small titanium screws into either the upper or lower jaw bones. These anchorage screws will protrude somewhat through the gum tissue. Your orthodontists will then apply a force to a tooth by stretching an elastic or applying a spring between the bracket on the tooth and the top part of the anchorage screw. Once the desired tooth movement is achieved, the anchorage screws are simply removed.</p>
      <p>Finally, simple soft tissue procedures like frenectomies are sometimes advised by the orthodontists. This entails removing the frenum, or muscle attachment and the thin layer of gum tissue covering the frenum, from under the upper lip. This prevents relapse of a diastema (space between the two front teeth) once it has been orthodontically closed.</p>
    </div>
  </SidebarLayout>
</Layout>
